To check if an array contains a specific string in JavaScript, you can use the `Array.prototype.includes()` method. Here's an example:

```javascript
const array = ['apple', 'banana', 'orange'];
const searchString = 'banana';

if (array.includes(searchString)) {
  console.log(`${searchString} is in the array`);
} else {
  console.log(`${searchString} is NOT in the array`);
}
```

In this example, we first define an array of fruits, and then define a string `'banana'` that we want to search for in the array. We then use the `.includes()` method to check if the array contains `'banana'`. If it does, we log a message indicating that the string is in the array. Otherwise, we log a message indicating that the string is not in the array.

Note that the `.includes()` method is case-sensitive, meaning that it will only match strings that have the same case as the search string. If you want to perform a case-insensitive search, you can convert the strings to lowercase using the `.toLowerCase()` method before performing the search.

If you want to check whether a string contains exactly one space character, you can use a regular expression pattern with the `String.prototype.match()` method. Here's an example:

```javascript
const text = 'hello world';

if (text.match(/^(\S+)\s(\S+)$/)) {
  console.log('There is exactly one space between the words');
} else {
  console.log('There is not exactly one space between the words');
}
```

In this example, we define a string `text` that contains two words separated by a single space. We then use the `match()` method with the following regular expression pattern: `/^(\S+)\s(\S+)$/`. This pattern matches the start of the string `^`, followed by one or more non-space characters `(\S+)`, followed by a space character `\s`, followed by one or more non-space characters `(\S+)`, followed by the end of the string `$`.

If the text matches the pattern (i.e. there is exactly one space character between the words), the `match()` method returns an array containing the matched text, and the `if` statement in the example evaluates to `true`. Otherwise, the `if` statement evaluates to `false`.

Note that this pattern assumes that the string contains only two words separated by a single space. If you want to match more than two words or allow multiple spaces between words, you will need to modify the pattern accordingly.

If you want to check whether a string contains exactly one space character, you can use the `String.prototype.indexOf()` method which returns the index of the first occurrence of the specified value in a string, or -1 if it is not found. You can use this method to find the position of the first space character, and then check if there are any more spaces after it. Here's an example:

```javascript
const text = 'hello world';

const spacePosition = text.indexOf(' ');
if (spacePosition !== -1 && text.indexOf(' ', spacePosition + 1) === -1) {
  console.log('There is exactly one space between the words');
} else {
  console.log('There is not exactly one space between the words');
}
```

In this example, we define a string `text` that contains two words separated by a single space. We then use the `indexOf()` method to find the position of the first space character in the string. If the position is not `-1`, which means that the space was found in the string, we check if there are any more spaces after it by calling `indexOf(' ', spacePosition + 1)`. If this call returns `-1`, it means that there are no more spaces in the string after the first space, and we can conclude that there is exactly one space between the words.

Note that this method assumes that the string contains only two words separated by a single space. If you want to match more than two words or allow multiple spaces between words, you will need to modify the logic accordingly.

To replace multiple spaces with a single space in a string in JavaScript, you can use the `String.prototype.replace()` method with a regular expression. Here's an example:

```javascript
const text = 'This   is   a   test     string    with    multiple spaces';

const cleanText = text.replace(/\s+/g, ' ');

console.log(cleanText);
// Output: 'This is a test string with multiple spaces'
```

In this example, we define a string `text` that contains multiple spaces. We then use the `replace()` method with the regular expression `/\s+/g` to match one or more consecutive whitespace characters (spaces, tabs, line breaks, etc.), and replace them with a single space. The `g` flag specifies that the regular expression should be applied globally, meaning all occurrences of the pattern within the string will be replaced.

The resulting string is stored in the `cleanText` variable and logged to the console. The output shows that all occurrences of multiple consecutive spaces have been replaced with a single space.

Note that the regular expression pattern `/\s+/g` matches all whitespace characters, not just spaces. If you want to match only spaces, you can use the regular expression `/ {2,}/g`, which matches two or more consecutive spaces.

To delete all non-digits in a string in JavaScript, you can use the `String.prototype.replace()` method with a regular expression that matches non-digit characters. Here's an example:

```javascript
const text = 'abc123def456ghi789';

const digitsOnly = text.replace(/\D/g, '');

console.log(digitsOnly);
// Output: '123456789'
```

In this example, we define a string `text` that contains both letters and digits. We then use the `replace()` method with the regular expression `/\D/g` to match all non-digit characters in the string, and replace them with an empty string. The `g` flag specifies that the regular expression should be applied globally, meaning all occurrences of the pattern within the string will be replaced.

The resulting string, containing only the digits, is stored in the `digitsOnly` variable and logged to the console. The output shows that all non-digit characters have been removed from the original string.

Note that the regular expression pattern `\D` matches all non-digit characters including white spaces, dots, commas, etc. If you want to match only digits (e.g. `0-9`), you can use the regular expression `/[^0-9]/g` instead. This will match any character that is not a digit and replace it with an empty string.

To iterate over an object in JavaScript and get its keys and values separately, you can use a `for...in` loop to iterate over the object's keys, and use the keys to access the corresponding values. Here's an example:

```javascript
const obj = {a: "1", b: "2"};

for (const key in obj) {
  if (obj.hasOwnProperty(key)) {
    const value = obj[key];
    console.log(`Key: ${key}, Value: ${value}`);
  }
}
```

In this example, we define an object with two properties, `a` and `b`, each with a corresponding value. We then use a `for...in` loop to iterate over the keys in the object. For each key, we check if the object has the key as its own property (.hasOwnProperty()), then use the key to access the corresponding value with `obj[key]`.

We then log a string to the console that shows both the key and value using string interpolation.

The output of the code will be:

```
Key: a, Value: 1
Key: b, Value: 2
```

This shows that the `for...in` loop has correctly iterated over the object's keys, and we have been able to access both the keys and values separately inside the loop.
